# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-sign-language-grammar
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz is a Northwest Caucasian language and is thus related to Adyghe.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The language of Abkhaz is especially close to Abaza, and they are sometimes considered dialects of the same language, Abazgi, of which the literary dialects of Abkhaz and Abaza are simply two ends of a dialect continuum.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Grammatically, the two are very similar; however, the differences in phonology are substantial, it also contains elements characteristic of Kabardian; these are the main reasons for many others to prefer keeping the two separate, while others still refer to it as the Tapanta dialect of Abkhaz.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Chirikba mentions that there are possible indications that proto-Northwest Caucasian, could have divided firstly into proto-Circassian and to proto-Ubykh-Abkhaz; Ubykh then being the closest relative to Abkhaz, with it only later on being influenced by Circassian.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There is not an agreed number of speakers of Abkhaz, and there are widely different numbers.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] It is agreed that today most of the Abkhaz people do not live in Abkhazia.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In the census conducted by the Republic of Abkhazia in 2011, Abkhazians comprised 50.8% of the population, around 122,175 people; of these 92,838 spoke it natively.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Only two of the original dialects are still spoken in Abkhazia.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The Bzyp dialect is still spoken in its homeland northwest of Sukhumi, stretching from the Bzyp River to the western environs of Sukhumi and the Psyrtskha valley, whereas the Abzhywa dialect is spoken south-east of Sukhumi.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The rest of the Abkhaz speaking population inhabits other neighbouring areas.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The exact number of Abkhazians and Abkhaz speakers in Turkey is not clear.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The Turkish census denotes 13,951, but the figures are dubious, since the numbers of Abkhazians that came from the beginning of the 19th century to the middle of the 20th have been documented at around 30 thousand.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] *Ethnologue* gives 150,000 Abkhazians living in Turkey, of these 50,000 still speak the language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The head of the Abkhaz federation says there are in between 500 and 700 thousand Abkhazians in Turkey.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Historically the dialects of Sadz, Ahchypsy and Tsabal were located in Abkhazia; Sadz being spoken from the Bzyp river to the Matsesta River, and further to the north-west bordering the Sochypsta River.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Today they are exclusively spoken in the northwestern part of Turkey, specially in the Sakarya province, it being spoken in 14 villages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The other major place where Abkhaz is spoken is in Karachay-Cherkessia, where the Northern dialects are spoken, although there they are considered as a separate language and form the literary Abaza language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] They are spoken by 37,831 people in Russia, mostly in the south of Stavropol Krai in the area around Kislovodsk, and in the upper Kuma river area.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz is also spoken as a minority language around the world.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There is a considerable number of Abkhaz speakers in Adjara in southern Georgia, with the diaspora concentrating itself around the capital Batumi, with about 982 people considering Abkhaz their first language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In the Russian census of 2010, 6,786 speakers of Abkhaz were reported in Russia.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In Ukraine there are around 1,458 according to the 2001 census, but of these only 317 speak Abkhazian.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There were also communities in Syria, Jordan and Iraq with around 5,000 Abkhazians, although this number could reach 10,000 according to the Abkhazia's Foreign Ministry.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The biggest western diaspora is in Germany, with around 5,000 speakers, but other communities are found in countries such as the United States, United Kingdom, Austria, France, Belgium and so on.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The earliest indisputable extant written records of the Abkhaz language are in the Arabic script, recorded by the Turkish traveller Evliya Çelebi in the 17th century.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has been used as a literary language for only about 100 years.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] It was suggested that certain inscriptions on Ancient Greek pottery which had been considered nonsense are in fact written in Abkhaz-Adydge languages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The methodology of the research was criticised and the results called improbable.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In 1918, Tbilisi State University became the first institution of higher education to teach Abkhazian language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The founders of the university began to take care of the development and scientific study of the Abkhazian language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] At the meeting of the Council of Professors held at Tbilisi State University in 1918, Ivane Javakhishvili noted the scientific importance of studying Caucasian languages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In 1918, by the decision of the Council of Professors, Petre Charaia was invited to teach the Abkhazian language, and from 1925, this mission was continued by Dimitri Gulia and Simon Janashia.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Both Georgian and Abkhaz law enshrines an official status of the Abkhaz language in Abkhazia.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The 1992 law of Georgia, reiterated in the 1995 constitution, grants Abkhaz the status of second official language in the territory of Abkhazia — along with Georgian.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In November 2007, the de facto authorities of Abkhazia adopted a new law "on the state language of the Republic of Abkhazia" that mandates Abkhaz as the language of official communication.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The law is an attempt to amend a situation where up to a third of the ethnic Abkhaz population are no longer capable of speaking their ethnic language, and even more are unable to read or write it; instead, Russian is the language most commonly used in public life at present.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The literary language is based on the Abzhywa dialect.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In some form or the other, all dialects are richer in phonemes than the standard Abzhywa dialect.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The only dialects spoken in Abkhazia are Abzhywa and Bzyp.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Northern dialects which are the basis for literary Abaza are spoken in Karachay-Cherkessia, while the other dialects such as Sadz are spoken in Turkey due to Russian invasions in the 19th century.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] While most differences are phonetic, differences in the lexicon are present, although mostly due to exterior contact.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Bzyp contains the most preserved lexicon, with few borrowings.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abzhywa has adopted many loans from Kartvelian, specially Mingrelian; Sadz on the other hand has more words from Circassian.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Northern dialects in general have more loanwords from Persian, Arabic, Turkish and Circassian.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has a very large number of consonants (58 in the literary dialect), with three-way voiced/voiceless/ejective and palatalized/labialized/plain distinctions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] By contrast, the language has only two phonemically distinct vowels, which have several allophones depending on the palatal and/or labial quality of adjacent consonants.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Labialised alveolo-palatal fricatives are found in the Bzyp and Sadz dialects of Abkhaz, but not in Abzhywa.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Plain alveolo-palatal consonants and the pharyngealised and labialised-pharyngealised uvular fricatives are unique to the Bzyp dialect.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The consonants highlighted in red and in brackets are the 4 kinds of labialisation described by Chirikba.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Found in the Bzyp and Sadz dialects of Abkhaz, but not in Abzhywa.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The nature of the vowels of Abkhaz is not clear.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Some linguists, characterise the vowel system as a 2 degree vertical vowel system; with the two vowels being distinguished by height, 'ә' being the high/close vowel, and 'а' being the low/open.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] This system would very closely resemble the one found in Adyghe.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The quality of 'ә' in this case, is usually represented as [ɨ] if the vowel is in a stressed position, and being unaffected by its neighbouring consonants.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Other linguists however, mainly Russian ones, describe the vowels differently.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] They describe the sound of 'ә' being completely different from [ɨ], and by their descriptions being closer to [ə].
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The 'а' is described as being particularly back, likely [ɑ].
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has used the Cyrillic script since 1862.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The first alphabet was a 37-character Cyrillic alphabet invented by Baron Peter von Uslar.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In 1909 a 55-letter Cyrillic alphabet was used.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] A 75-letter Latin script devised by a Russian/Georgian linguist Nikolai Marr lasted for 2 years 1926–1928 (during the Latinization campaign).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The Georgian script was adopted and used between 1938 and 1954, after that the initial Cyrillic alphabet, designed in 1892 by Dmitry Gulia together with Konstantin Machavariani and modified in 1909 by Aleksey Chochua, was restored to use.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The Latin alphabet in Abkhaz is currently not in Unicode.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Typical of Northwest Caucasian languages, Abkhaz is an agglutinative language that relies heavily on affixation.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] It has an ergative-absolutive typology, such that the subject of an intransitive verb functions identically to the object of a transitive verb.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Notably, Abkhaz expresses ergativity entirely through the ordering of subjects and objects within verb constructions rather than through overt case marking as most other ergative languages do.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] All Latin transliterations in this section utilize the system explicated in Chirikba (2003) (see Abkhaz alphabet for the details).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz, being an ergative language, makes a strong distinction between transitive and intransitive verbs, as well as dynamic and stative.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs describe states of being, roughly analogous to copular phrases in English, as in дхәыҷуп (*d-x˚əčә́-wə-p* - "she is a child").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs express direct actions, functioning more closely to standard English verbs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs possess the full range of aspect, mood and tense forms, in contrast to statives, which do not.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Some verbs, called inversives, combine certain features of both stative and dynamic verbs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Another important verbal distinction in Abkhaz is finite versus non-finite.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Finite verbs usually contain enough information to form a complete sentence, whereas non-finite verbs typically form dependent clauses.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Verb stems can be derived in a number of ways, including compounding, affixation, reduplication or conversion from another part of speech.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Roughly equivalent to the infinitive, or to a so-called "verbal noun," the **Masdar** form of the verb resembles the English gerund.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] It is formed by the addition of a specific suffix to a bare verb stem, -ра (*-ra*) for a dynamic verb and -заара (*-zaara*) for a stative.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] However, the fully conjugated personal Abkhaz verb forms are "templatic," with each grammatical distinction occupying a specific "slot" or "position" within the broader verb template.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Verbs are thus formed by the addition of various affixes to the verb stem; these affixes express such distinctions as transitivity, person and stative/dynamic quality, occupying rigid positions within the overall verb structure.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There is a high degree of agreement between verbs and other parts of speech.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Not all of these elements will necessarily co-occur in every verb.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The individual parts of verb morphology are addressed below.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The first prefixing element of the verb complex expresses either the subject of an intransitive verb in the absolutive construction, or the direct object of a transitive verb in an ergative construction.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The following table illustrates the various agreement markers which can occupy the first position.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] These prefixes can either be in their long forms, containing the letters inside the parenthesis, or in the short forms that do not contain them.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] If the stress falls on the prefix, the long form is used.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] If the prefix is not followed by a consonant cluster, the short form is used.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] If the stress does not fall on the prefix, the short form is used.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] It is also possible for the possessive prefix ҽы́- (*čə́-*) in a reflexive construction or the relative prefix иы́- (*jә́-*) in a non-finite construction to occupy this position.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The second position is occupied by the indirect object or by the prefix аи- (*aj-*) for reciprocal pronouns equivalent to "each other" or "one another" in English.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] This position accommodates a number of prefixes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Any indirect object occurring after the one in the second position occupies this position instead; a possessive prefix of stative verbs can also be placed here.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Where a possessive prefix exists in the first position, the reflexive prefix is placed here.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] This position is occupied by preverbal elements which are not an explicit part of the verb stem.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Preverbal elements that are explicitly attached to the verb stem take this position.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The agreement marker corresponding to the agent (the subject of a transitive verb) takes this position.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The negation prefix m- occupies this position in a dynamic verb construction.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The causative prefix r- takes the final position before the verb stem.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The first of the suffixing elements expresses adverbial information relating to "inside" (-la) or "outside" (-aa).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Several aspect markers occupy this position as suffixes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Several tense markers occupy this position, dependent upon whether the verb in question is stative or dynamic.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs have a richly developed tense paradigm incorporating tense and aspect distinctions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The table below illustrates these various dynamic tense forms using the verb агара (*agara* – "to take").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs, by contrast, lack this rich tense system, as illustrated below using the verb а́цәара (*ácºara* - "to be sleeping").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The negation prefix m- occupies this position in a stative verb construction.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The final position in the verb complex can accommodate any one of several mixed purpose markers.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The **imperative** takes a few possible forms, depending upon the type of verb.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs form the imperative by the addition of agreement suffixes to a bare verb stem; intransitives include the subject and indirect object makers, whereas transitives include the direct object and absolutive.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs form the imperative simply by adding the durative suffix -z to the verb stem.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz lacks diathetic opposition, and as such there is no true passive voice distinction.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Like verbs, Abkhaz nouns are formed by the addition of various prefixes and suffixes to a static noun stem.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Noun stems can be derived according to several different processes, including compounding, reduplication, or the addition of a derivational affix.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The affixes mark number, definiteness and possession, as well as some case-like elements.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] As with verbs, not all of these elements can occur at the same time.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The individual parts of noun morphology are addressed below.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There is a range of definiteness in Abkhaz.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Those articles adhering to definite/generic categories appear as prefixes in the broader noun structure, whereas the indefinite is suffixed.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The absence of either article affix implies a zero reference implying universal quantifiers, or to express the total lack of a referent.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Definite and indefinite affixes may appear together in the same noun, implying that the referents are meant as a group or body.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There are some semantic differences in article usage between the different dialects of Abkhaz.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] These are possessive prefixes which express grammatical person and noun class.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] They come in two forms, the full and short ones.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The full ones contain the vowels inside the parenthesis, whereas the short ones do not.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] These few prefixes add numeric information to the noun complex.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Often, this takes the form of a numeral.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Inflectional suffixes can follow each other sequentially.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz distinguishes singular and plural; the singular is unmarked, whereas the plural is indicated by noun class-dependent suffixes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There are several pluralizing suffixes, but the two most commonly used refer generally to the human and non-human noun classes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There are instances where explicitly human nouns take non-human plural markers.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] There are also several plural endings that are of much narrower use.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The clitic -гьы (*-g’ə*) functions as an in-built coordinating conjunction.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Nouns in Abkhaz are classified broadly according to a human/non-human paradigm, with the human class itself further subdivided into masculine and feminine gender.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Gender is a fairly weak concept in Abkhaz grammar, and gender distinctions undergo a fair degree of neutralization in several contexts, including personal pronouns, verb agreement and possession marking.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] This class and gender system distinguishes Abkhaz from the other Northwest Caucasian languages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Although there is no special vocative declension, the prefix уа- (*wa-*), when attached to a noun stem, can express a vocative form.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Similarly, the suffix -a can be added to a proper noun ending in a consonant to communicate respect and endearment.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Pronouns are not inflected, and verbal agreement is generally sufficient to indicate grammatical person.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] It is common in everyday speech to use a short version of the pronoun which omits the suffix -рá (*-rá*), although this is done less frequently with third-person pronouns.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] In addition to noun-marking, **possession** can be indicated by adding the suffix -тәы́ (*-t’˚ә́*) to the short version of a personal pronoun.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Morphologically, adjectives are very similar to nouns, differing only in their syntactic function.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Similarly to nouns, adjective stems can be derived by compounding, reduplication and affixation.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] When used attributively, adjectives follow the noun that they modify.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Predicative adjectives, or those derived by suffixation, precede the noun.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The possessive prefix r- is used to show possessive agreement.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] These suffixes are added to the adjective stem to show agreement with the noun being modified.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The comparative form of an adjective is formed using the comparative particle аиҳá (*ajhá* - "more"), which precedes the adjective.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] The superlative form is indicated by the intensifier suffix -ӡа.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] Дарбанзаалак ауаҩы дшоуп ихы дақәиҭны. Ауаа зегь зинлеи патулеи еиҟароуп. Урҭ ирымоуп ахшыҩи аламыси, дара дарагь аешьеи аешьеи реиԥш еизыҟазароуп.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/abkhaz-language] "All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] An **adverb** is a word or an expression that generally modifies a verb, an adjective, another adverb, a determiner, a clause, a preposition, or a sentence.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Adverbs typically express manner, place, time, frequency, degree, or level of certainty by answering questions such as *how*, *in what way*, *when*, *where*, *to what extent*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] This is called the adverbial function and may be performed by an individual adverb, by an adverbial phrase, or by an adverbial clause.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Adverbs are traditionally regarded as one of the parts of speech.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] The English word *adverb* derives (through French) from Latin *adverbium*, from *ad-* ('to'), *verbum* ('word', 'verb'), and the nominal suffix *- ium*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] The term implies that the principal function of adverbs is to act as modifiers of verbs or verb phrases.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] An adverb used in this way may provide information about the manner, place, time, frequency, certainty, or other circumstances of the activity denoted by the verb or verb phrase.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Adverbs can also be used as modifiers of adjectives, and of other adverbs, often to indicate degree.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Adverbs thus perform a wide range of modifying functions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] The major exception is the function of modifier of nouns, which is performed instead by adjectives (compare *she sang loudly* with *her loud singing disturbed me*; here the verb *sang* is modified by the adverb *loudly*, whereas the noun *singing* is modified by the adjective *loud*).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] The word *even* in the first sentence is an adjective, since it is a prepositive modifier that modifies the noun *numbers*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] When the function of an adverb is performed by an expression consisting of more than one word, it is called an adverbial phrase or adverbial clause, or simply an adverbial.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] In English, adverbs of manner (answering the question *how?*) are often formed by adding *-ly* to adjectives, but flat adverbs (such as in *drive fast*, *drive slow*, and *drive friendly*) have the same form as the corresponding adjective.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Many other adverbs, however, are not related to adjectives in this way; they may be derived from other words or phrases, or may be single morphemes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Examples of such adverbs in English include *here, there, together, yesterday, aboard, very, almost*, etc.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Where the meaning permits, adverbs may undergo comparison, taking comparative and superlative forms.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] In English this is usually done by adding *more* and *most* before the adverb (*more slowly, most slowly*), although there are a few adverbs that take inflected forms, such as *well*, for which *better* and *best* are used.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] For more information about the formation and use of adverbs in English, see English adverbs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] For other languages, see § In other languages below, and the articles on individual languages and their grammars.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Adverbs are considered a part of speech in traditional English grammar, and are still included as a part of speech in grammar taught in schools and used in dictionaries.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] However, modern grammarians recognize that words traditionally grouped together as adverbs serve a number of different functions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Some describe adverbs as a "catch-all" category that includes all words that do not belong to one of the other parts of speech.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] A logical approach to dividing words into classes relies on recognizing which words can be used in a certain context.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] When this approach is taken, it is seen that adverbs fall into a number of different categories.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] For example, some adverbs can be used to modify an entire sentence, whereas others cannot.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Even when a sentential adverb has other functions, the meaning is often not the same.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Words like *very* afford another example.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] *Perry is very fast* is grammatical, but not *Perry very won the race*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] These words can modify adjectives but not verbs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] On the other hand, there are words like *here* and *there* that cannot modify adjectives.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] *The sock looks good there* is grammatical, but not *It is a there beautiful sock*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] The fact that many adverbs can be used in more than one of these functions can confuse the issue, and it may seem like splitting hairs to say that a single adverb is really two or more words that serve different functions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] However, this distinction can be useful, especially when considering adverbs like *naturally* that have different meanings in their different functions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Rodney Huddleston distinguishes between a *word* and a *lexicogrammatical-word*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Grammarians find difficulty categorizing negating words, such as the English *not*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adverb] Although traditionally listed as an adverb, this word does not behave grammatically like any other, and it probably should be placed in a class of its own.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Unlike the majority of languages in the world which follow the Nominative–accusative alignment, Adyghe follows the Ergative–absolutive alignment.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The distinction between syntactic cases is crucial for understanding who is doing the action and to whom.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Here, "table" has the absolutive case mark -р /-r/ while "man" has the ergative case mark -м /-m/.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] We also have the verb "break" in intransitive form "мэкъутэ" and transitive form "екъутэ".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In the example above, we specifically used SOV (Subject-Object-Verb) order, but Circassian allows any word order.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Adyghe nouns inflect for number, case, and definiteness.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The plural suffix is **-хэ** (*унэ* "house" → *унэхэр* "houses"), though plural meaning is often carried by the verb instead.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Collective nouns such as *жылэ* "village" and *унагъо* "family" act as a plurale tantum: they take no plural suffix but trigger plural agreement elsewhere.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] A definite noun carries a case marker, while an indefinite one is usually unmarked (*кӏалэ* "a boy" vs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The third-person pronouns double as demonstratives and use suppletive forms rather than the regular suffixes: *ар* / *ахэр* (absolutive) and *ащ* / *ахэм* (ergative–oblique).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] When a noun is followed by an adjective, the case suffix attaches to the adjective rather than the noun (*пшъэшъэ дахэр* "the pretty girl").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Possession is shown with the prefix **и-** on the possessed noun (*икӏалэ* "his/her boy"), and adjectives can become abstract nouns with **-агъэ** (*дахэ* "pretty" → *дахагъэ* "beauty").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] New nouns are also formed by compounding and by productive suffixes such as *-пӏэ* "place" (*еджапӏэ* "school") and *-кӏо* "agent" (*еджакӏо* "student").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Adyghe is a pro-drop language, so subject and object pronouns are often omitted because the verb marks person and number.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Possession is a key grammatical feature in Adyghe.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Inalienable possession is marked by a specific set of prefixes attached directly to the noun stem.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Alienable possession is used for separable items, such as property, animals, concepts, and material objects.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] These prefixes differ from the inalienable ones, typically involving the additional vowel **-и-** (-i-).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In Adyghe, pronouns are categorized into the following groups: personal, demonstrative, possessive, interrogative, determinative/reflexive, and indefinite.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Strictly speaking, personal pronouns exist only for the **first** and **second** persons.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] To express the **third person** ("he", "she", "it", "they"), Adyghe uses **demonstrative pronouns** (see below).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Unlike nouns, 1st and 2nd person pronouns do not distinguish between the Absolutive and Ergative cases.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] These two cases merge into a common form.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Demonstrative pronouns are used to point to objects and also function as 3rd person pronouns.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Unlike personal pronouns, demonstrative pronouns **do** distinguish cases.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Independent possessive pronouns express ownership ("Mine", "Yours", "Theirs").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] These differ from the possessive prefixes (си-, уи-, etc.) attached to nouns.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Interrogative pronouns are used to ask questions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] This group includes reflexive pronouns ("self") and quantifiers ("all", "every").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The primary indefinite pronoun in Adyghe is **зыгорэ**, which corresponds to "someone", "something", "some", or "one".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Adyghe adjectives are morphologically close to nouns and share their number and case markers.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The same holds for adjectives that behave as suffixes, such as the augmentative *-шхо* "big" (*унэшхохэр* "the big houses").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Qualitative adjectives ("good", "tall") follow the noun, while relative or material adjectives ("iron", "wooden") precede it and do not inflect (*гъучӏ пӏэкӏорыр* "the iron bed").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Used on its own, an adjective declines like a noun through all four cases (*фыжьыр* "the white one", *фыжьым* "of/to the white one").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Degree is expressed analytically: the comparative with the particle *нахь* "more" (*Ар ощ нахь лъагэ* "He is taller than you") and the superlative with *анахь* "most" (*Ар пшъашъэмэ анахь дахэ* "She is the most beautiful of the girls").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Adjectives also feed productive derivation.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The suffix **-гъэ** turns them into abstract nouns of measure (*кӏыхьэ* "long" → *кӏыхьагъэ* "length"; *дахэ* "beautiful" → *дэхагъэ* "beauty"), while **-гъакӏэ** forms nouns for the state or essence of a quality (*дэхэгъакӏэ* "(inherent) prettiness").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The prefix **шӏо-** forms psychological predicates meaning "X is [adjective] to someone" (*дахэ* "beautiful" → *шӏодах* "it is beautiful to him/her").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In the Adyghe language, adverbs are categorized into four main groups: adverbs of place, adverbs of time, adverbs of quality (manner), and adverbs of amount (quantity).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] These adverbs indicate location or direction.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] These adverbs indicate when an action takes place.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] These adverbs indicate the degree or quantity of the action or quality.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Adverbs of manner describe *how* an action is performed.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] They are productively formed from qualitative adjectives using the adverbial case suffix ~эу (/~aw/).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] **Concatenating (Compounding):** Combining two words.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] **Conversion (Fossilized Cases):** Nouns fixed in a specific case functioning as adverbs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The word нахь (/naːħ/) functions as an adversative adverb meaning "rather" or "actually." It is used to correct a statement or introduce a contrast to what the listener might believe.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In English, the word "and" is used to connect various parts of speech.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In Adyghe, there are different ways (suffixes) to connect words depending on their part of speech and definiteness.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The independent conjunction ыкӏи /ət͡ʃəj/ ("and") can also be used to connect different parts of speech.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Conjunctions in the Circassian language play the same role like in English, they are used to connect together, in different ways, words or parts of a difficult sentence.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] According to structure of Circassian conjunctions they can be separated into two groups: simple and complex.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Particles in the Circassian language vary in both meaning and structure.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Semantically, they are categorized into groups such as affirmative, negative, interrogative, intensive, indicatory, and stimulating.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Adyghe has a four-way demonstrative system based on distance and visibility, plus an interrogative form.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Demonstrative stems combine with various suffixes to form adverbs and pronouns related to location, manner, and time.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In the Circassian language, as well as in other Ibero-Caucasian languages, role of prepositions belongs to postpositions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] It is difficult to define the exact count of postpositions in the Circassian language, because even such major parts of speech as nouns (from the point of view of their functionality) sometimes can be included into the group, together with some verb prefixes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Nouns and adverbs sometimes play role of postpositions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] For example, nous that describe different parts of human body (head, nose, side and so on) sometimes function as postpositions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] For example: Шъузыр лӏым ыпэ итэу кӏощтыгъэ "The wife was going in front of the husband" (the preposition "in front of" in the Circassian sentence is expressed by the phrase ыпэ итэу "being in front of his nose").
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Nouns and pronouns combine with a postposition in the ergative grammatical case only.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Postpositions can attach possessive prefixes to themselves.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The suffix ~a /aː/ initials the interrogative particle that indicates a yes-or-no question.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Кӏала ӏаным тесыр? – Is it a boy that sits on the table?
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Кӏалэр ӏаным теса? – Is the boy sits on the table?
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Кӏалэр ӏана зытесыр? – Is it a table the boy is sits on?
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] If question is posited to word having the negative suffix ~п (~p), it is converted to suffix ~ба (~baː).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] The suffix ~ба /baː/ initials the negative interrogative particle.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Кӏалэба ӏаным тесыр? – Isn't it a boy that sits on the table?
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Кӏалэр ӏаным тесыба? – Isn't the boy sits on the table?
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Кӏалэр ӏанэба зытесыр? – Isn't it a table the boy is sits on?
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Order of words in a Circassian sentence is, generally, free, but the situation where verb goes at the end is the most typical.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Трактористыр пасэу къэтэджыгъ "The tractor-driver got up early".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Structure of a full sentence is, usually, defined by its form of verb.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Sentence, where subject is in zero form.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In this type of sentences both transitive and intransitive verbs can be used: Нанэ тхъу къыситыгъ "Mother gave me some butter"; Кӏэлэ тэрэз ащ фэдэу псэурэ́п "A good guy does not behave like that".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] This type of Circassian sentences is rarer than the first two.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In the Circassian language there are compound sentences that can consist both of independent parts only, and of the main part in combination with dependent subparts.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Compound sentences with dependent parts are structurally different.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Мэзэ́ псау́м ащ ӏоф ышӏагъэ́п, сыда пӏомэ дэсыгъэпы́шъ ары́ "He has not worked for the whole month, because he has been away".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] шъэрэ зырэ (ʂara zəra) [101], шъэрэ тӀурэ (ʂara tʷʼəra) [102], шъэрэ пшӀыкӀузырэ (pʃʼəkʷʼətʷʼəra) [111], шъитӀурэ щэкӀырэ плӀырэ (ʂitʷʼəra ɕat͡ʃəra pɬʼəra) [234]).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] When there is a certain amount of the noun, the noun is followed by -и (-i) and the multiplier digit root.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] ятӀунэрэ – second (jaːtʷʼənara), ящынэрэ – third (jaːɕənara), яплӀынэрэ – fourth (jaːpɬʼənara).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] Япэрэ мафэ – First day (jaːpara maːfa), ЯтӀонэрэ мафэ – second day (jaːtʷʼənara maːfa), ЯтӀонэрэ цуакъо – second shoe (jaːpara t͡ʃʷaːqʷa), Яхэнэрэ классым щегъэжьагъэу тутын сешъо~I have been smoking since the sixth class.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] о плӀэрэ къыосӀогъах – I have told you four times already.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] щы /ɕə/ "three" – щанэ /ɕaːna/ "third", плӏы /pɬʼə/ "four" – плӏанэ /pɬʼaːna/ "fourth", хы "six" – ханэ /xaːna/ "sixth" and so on.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] зырыз /zərəz/ "by one", тӏурытӏу /tʷʼərətʷʼ/ "by twos", щырыщ /ɕərəɕ/ "by threes", плӏырыплӏ /pɬʼərəplʼ/ "by fours", тфырытф /tfərətf/ "by fives" and so on.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In a sentence: Еджакӏохэр экзаменым тӏурытӏоу чӏахьэщтыгъэх "Pupils entered the examination room by twos".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] зыхыбл /zəxəbl/ зы-хы-бл "about six or seven", зытӏущ /zətʷʼəɕ/ зы-тӏу-щ "about two or three".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/adyghe-grammar] In a sentence: Непэ садэжь нэбгырэ зытӀущ къыӀухьагъ "About two or three people have approached me today".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/american-sign-language-grammar] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:american-sign-language-grammar/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
